-- Copper, Oil Decline as Wheat Climbs: Commodities at Close
-- B y   J o h n   D e a n e
-- 2012-04-23T16:13:30Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-04-23/copper-oil-decline-as-wheat-climbs-commodities-at-close.html
The Standard & Poor’s GSCI gauge of
24 commodities fell 0.8 percent to 670.65 at 5 p.m. in  London .
The UBS Bloomberg CMCI index of 26 raw materials was down 0.7
percent at 1,554.012.  BASE METALS  Copper headed for the biggest loss in more than a week in
New York on concern that demand will slow as manufacturing
contracts in China, the world’s biggest user of the metal, and
 Europe  struggles to stem its debt crisis.  Copper futures for July delivery slid 2.2 percent to $3.624
a pound on the Comex in New York. On the London Metal Exchange,
copper for delivery in three months fell 2.3 percent to
$8,002.50 a metric ton ($3.63 a pound).  Aluminum, zinc, lead, nickel and tin also retreated in
London.  PRECIOUS METALS  Gold declined to a two-week low as a stronger dollar curbed
demand for the metal as an alternative investment. Silver
slumped to a three-month low.  Gold futures for June delivery fell 0.8 percent to
$1,629.60 an ounce on the Comex in  New York . Earlier, prices
slipped to $1,623.60, the lowest for a most-active contract
since April 5.  Silver futures for July delivery slid 3.1 percent to
$30.745 an ounce on the Comex after dropping to $30.63, the
lowest since Jan. 20.  CRUDE OIL  Oil declined the most in two weeks as manufacturing shrank
in China and the euro-area, bolstering concern that fuel
consumption will diminish.  Crude oil for June delivery decreased $1.67, or 1.6
percent, to $102.21 a barrel on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.  Brent oil for June settlement dropped 94 cents, or 0.8
percent, to $117.82 a barrel on the London-based ICE exchange.  OIL PRODUCTS  Gasoline sank to a seven-week low on signs that
manufacturing is slowing in  China  and Europe, raising concern
the global recovery is stalled and fuel demand will decline.  Gasoline for May delivery fell 2.79 cents, or 0.9 percent,
to $3.1148 a gallon on the New York Mercantile Exchange. Prices
touched $3.1052, the lowest since Feb. 29.  Regular gasoline at the pump, averaged nationwide, fell 0.5
cent to $3.858 a gallon yesterday, according to AAA, the
nation’s biggest motoring club. Prices have dropped 7.8 cents
since reaching a 2012 high of $3.936 on April 4.  Heating oil for May delivery fell 2.6 cents, or 0.8
percent, to $3.1116 a gallon on the exchange.  GRAINS, OILSEEDS  Corn rose on speculation that China, the world’s largest
pork consumer, will buy more U.S. grain to meet expanding demand
for feed from hog producers. Wheat also advanced.  Corn futures for July delivery rose 1 percent to $6.0875 a
bushel on the  Chicago  Board of Trade.  Wheat futures for July delivery rose 1.2 percent to $6.3075
a bushel on the CBOT, heading for a second gain in three
sessions.  LIVESTOCK  Cattle futures slumped to the lowest in more than a week on
signs of increasing U.S. beef supplies. Hog prices rose.  Cattle futures for June delivery slid 0.6 percent to
$1.1475 a pound on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. Earlier,
prices reached $1.1425, the lowest for a most-active contract
since April 11.  Hog futures for June settlement climbed 0.4 percent to
87.725 cents a pound on the CME.  Feeder-cattle futures for August settlement declined 0.8
percent to $1.54025 a pound in Chicago.  SOFT COMMODITIES  Cocoa fell the most in more than two weeks on renewed
concern that a slowing global economy will crimp demand for raw
materials. Coffee, sugar and orange juice also slid. Cotton
rose.  Cocoa for July delivery sank 2.7 percent to $2,207 a metric
ton on ICE Futures U.S. in New York. A close at that level would
mark the biggest decline for a most-active contract since April
4.  Arabica-coffee futures for July delivery lost 0.7 percent
to $1.777 a pound in New York, heading for the first decline
since April 17.  Raw-sugar futures for July delivery slid 0.1 percent to
21.52 cents a pound, after touching 21.41, the lowest since May
23, on ICE.  Also in New York, orange-juice futures for July delivery
tumbled 2.4 percent to $1.4705 a pound, while cotton futures for
July delivery gained 0.7 percent to 91.68 cents a pound.  In London futures trading, cocoa and robusta coffee and
also declined on NYSE Liffe, while refined sugar was little
changed.  NATURAL GAS  Natural gas futures rose in New York from near decade lows
as forecasts for cooler weather on the eastern U.S. signaled
increased demand for the heating fuel.  Natural gas for May delivery rose 3 cents, or 1.6 percent,
$1.957 per million British thermal units on the  New York
Mercantile Exchange . The futures have dropped 35 percent
this year.  To contact the reporter on this story:
